{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":98090,"duration_api_ms":98057,"num_turns":3,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"2e7d6f62-879d-4dc4-98a3-484e5aa917ec","total_cost_usd":0.3392371,"usage":{"input_tokens":4,"cache_creation_input_tokens":23589,"cache_read_input_tokens":76002,"output_tokens":2023,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":23589,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":4,"outputTokens":2023,"cacheReadInputTokens":76002,"cacheCreationInputTokens":23589,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.23602725000000002,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":79,"outputTokens":5464,"cacheReadInputTokens":300021,"cacheCreationInputTokens":36647,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.10320985000000002,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"All four amendments identify genuine bugs or defects in the timeout and process management code. The dual-timeout race (fr-3-a95af876) makes artifact preservation dead code; the test gap (fr-3-e384feeb) fails to catch this; the non-Unix kill path (fr-3-1c23f8ce) leaks processes on Windows; and the exit-127 misclassification (fr-3-ccb079f3) creates false non-retryable failures for wrapper scripts.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-3-a95af876","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed by code review: service.rs:204 and process_backend.rs:1018 both use `request.timeout` as their duration, but the service-layer timeout wraps the entire invoke() call including build_command() and spawn() overhead. The outer timeout therefore fires first (or simultaneously), making the inner timeout's error path — and critically the `preserve_failed_artifacts` call at lines 1193-1196 — unreachable in production. This is a real bug: on timeout, diagnostic artifacts (schema files, last-message files) are silently lost instead of being preserved to runtime/failed. Either adding a buffer to the outer timeout or moving preservation into the cancel/cleanup path are both sound fixes."},{"amendment_id":"fr-3-e384feeb","decision":"accept","rationale":"The existing test at process_backend_test.rs:1990 only asserts the return type (FailureClass::Timeout) and message text, but never checks that the side effect — artifact preservation to runtime/failed — actually occurred. This is a meaningful gap: the artifact preservation is currently unreachable (per fr-3-a95af876), and this test would not catch that regression. Adding assertions for .failed.raw and Codex-specific schema/message files after timeout would provide proper coverage of the preservation guarantee."},{"amendment_id":"fr-3-1c23f8ce","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed: `send_sigkill()` returns `Err(Unsupported)` under `#[cfg(not(unix))]`, and `spawn_background_reap()` ignores that error with `let _ = child.send_sigkill().await`. The subsequent `child.wait().await` then blocks indefinitely because the process was never killed. The Arc<ManagedChild> is held by the background task, so `kill_on_drop` never fires. This is a genuine process leak on Windows — the timeout returns FailureClass::Timeout to the caller while the backend process continues running indefinitely. The fix should use platform-appropriate process termination (e.g., TerminateProcess on Windows) or at minimum drop the ManagedChild to trigger kill_on_drop."},{"amendment_id":"fr-3-ccb079f3","decision":"accept","rationale":"The amendment correctly identifies that exit code 127 is already handled at two earlier points: resolve_binary() returns BackendUnavailable for missing binaries in explicit search paths, and command.spawn() returns ErrorKind::NotFound which maps to BinaryNotFound. Once a process has successfully spawned and executed, exit code 127 is purely application-defined — shells and wrapper scripts commonly use 127 for their own error semantics (e.g., a CLI tool returning 127 for a subcommand-not-found error). Unconditionally mapping post-spawn exit 127 to non-retryable BinaryNotFound bypasses the retry budget for what may be a transient or recoverable application error. The classify_exit_failure function should treat 127 the same as other non-zero exits (TransportFailure) since the binary clearly existed if it was spawned."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"f070be7f-68b0-4298-89b7-143610468424"}
